  <span id="freeText11738113170156824810" style="display:none">"Equador" is a story about travels, expats, exotic places, intricate plots and very interesting and “alive” characters. Overall, the book is an amazing and somewhat disturbing journey about Luis Bernardo Valença, a 37 year old "dandy" from Lisbon that is sent to the archipelago of Sao Tomé e Principe to take charge as Governor in order to try to change the state of affairs concerning the almost-slave work that exists in the island. The objective is to try to avoid the commerce embargo by British merchants to São Tomé / Portuguese exports. The very clear and image writing of Miguel Sousa Tavares shines again as it brings back to life Lisbon in the early 1900's close to the end of the Monarchy, the island of São Tomé, India and really edgy characters put together in a gripping narrative. Personally, I could not help myself from relating the occurrences in the book with the times that I was an expat. All the amazing experiences that one goes through, but also, the new perils, huge challenges and memorable good and bad moments. The ending of the book is intense, surprising and disturbing. However, it is also elegantly knit together with the sense of duty that the main character evidences throughout his journey, and also, with the last days of the Monarchy and the assassination of the Portuguese King. The image of Conde de Arnoso watching the Tejo River from Terreiro de Paço, as he reflects upon Luis tragic ending and upon the end of the Monarchy, as an English frigate sails away, is a perfect ending image. A memorable tale.</span>
