  <span id="freeText14718260632523373317" style="display:none">In 1905, Luis Bernardo is a typical bon-vivant of the high society of Lisbon when he is invited to spend three years as governor of the colony of São Tomé and Príncipe, two "islets" in the middle of the ocean as the author likes to emphasize. The British are accusing the Portuguese of using slave labor on the islands and threatening to boycott their exports; Luis Bernardo's job is to clear the situation before that happens. (Note that Luis Bernardo is fictitious).<br /><br />Ecuador is a very interesting historical novel. The author shares a lot of information about the political situation in São Tomé and Portugal in the early 1900s (the end of the Portuguese monarchy), moving from fiction to nonfiction very easily and proving that he did a lot of historical research to write the book - at some points this narrative is more than enough, and sometimes underestimates the reader by mentioning things he had previously spoken. However, the characters are very well built, the story flows, the scenes are extremely rich in details.<br /><br />Unfortunately, and here is the critical point of the book, the author didn't avoid many clichés with some behaviors and stereotyped characters. I would attribute this to the fact that it’s a white author approach writing of historical slave fiction, which results in only a few lines in the book dedicated to nonwhite characters - although a slave rebellion is one of the climaxes of the novel. If the nonwhite characters had got more attention, I believe the story would be better.<br /><br />Anyway, I really enjoyed the historical setting and some of the plot twists, which left me intrigued to move forward. * Was really nice have the pleasure to read the book in the original language (Portuguese❤️).</span>
