  <span id="freeText942685552811535985" style="display:none">I was very happy to find a historical novel set on Sao Tome and Principe, islands off the coast of West Africa which I had never heard of before: formerly Portuguese colonies, producers of large amounts of cocoa. This novel is about the governor who in 1905 was sent to attempt to put an end to slavery on the islands (labourers were shipped there from Portuguese Angola). It is well researched and the descriptions of life on the islands, its climate and scenery, and the historical events are very well done. It is unfortunate that the descriptions of the Angolan people, even being portrayed as they are through the eyes of the sympathetic main character, are still quite demeaning, although I suppose he was trying to write the thought processes of a man of the period. As others have pointed out the author's treatment of women is also pretty sexist (with a couple of graphic sex scenes, eye-roll). So I have mixed feelings about the book and whether I would recommend it to others - but it is a fascinating story, and I am glad to have learned about this small part of the history of these remote, now independent African islands. I would love to visit them one day!</span>
